{"cursor":"65855","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0e/It-italiano.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a2/It-s%C3%AC.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4f/It-no.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/37/It-ciao.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/9e/It-arrivederci.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/02/It-per_favore.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e0/It-grazie.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/b8/It-scusi.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0b/It-non_capisco.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/09/It-parlate_inglese.ogg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6e/It-dov%27%C3%A8_il_bagno.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox language |name=Italian |nativename=Italiano, Lingua italiana\n|pronunciation= |states=Italy, San Marino, Malta, Switzerland, Vatican City,\nSlovenia (Slovenian Istria), Croatia (Istria County), Argentina, Brazil,\nAustralia |region=(widely known among older people and in commercial sectors in\nSomalia, Eritrea, and Libya; used in the Federal Government of Somalia)\n|speakers = 59 million Italian proper, native and native bilingual |date = 2007\n|ref = Nationalencyklopedin \"VÃ¤rldens 100 stÃ¶rsta sprÃ¥k 2007\" The World's\n100 Largest Languages in 2007 |speakers2= 85 million all varieties , February 2006 |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=Italic\n|fam3=Romance |fam4=Italo-Dalmatian |script=Latin (Italian alphabet) Italian\nBraille |nation= (Istria County) (Slovenian\nIstria) |agency=not officially by Accademia della Crusca |iso1=it|iso2=ita|iso3=ita|lingua=51-AAA-\nq |map= |notice=IPA }}\n\n'Italian' ( or lingua italiana) is a Romance language spoken mainly in Europe:\nItaly, Switzerland, San Marino, Vatican City, by minorities in Malta, Monaco,\nCroatia, Slovenia, France, Libya, Eritrea, and Somalia, [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=ita\nEthnologue report for language code:ita (Italy)] â Gordon, Raymond G., Jr.\n(ed.), 2005. Ethnologue: Languages of the World, Fifteenth edition. Dallas,\nTex.: SIL International. Online version and by expatriate communities in\nthe Americas and Australia. Many speakers are native bilinguals of both\nstandardised Italian and other regional\nlanguages. [http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=IT Languages of\nItaly] - Ethnologue - Languages of the World - Copyright Â© 2010 SIL\nInternational.\n\nAccording to the Bologna statistics of the European Union, Italian is spoken as\na mother tongue by 59 million people in the EU (13% of the EU population),\nmainly in Italy, and as a second language by 14 million (3%). Including the Italian speakers in non-EU European countries\n(such as Switzerland and Albania) and on other continents, the total number of\nspeakers is more than 85 million.\n\nIn Switzerland, Italian is one of four official languages; it is studied and\nlearned in all the confederation schools and spoken, as mother language, in the\nSwiss cantons of Ticino and Grigioni and by the Italian immigrants that are\npresent in large numbers in German- and French-speaking cantons. It is also the\nofficial language of San Marino, as well as the primary language of Vatican City. [http://www.vaticanstate.va/NR/rdonlyres/FBFEA0E8-B43A-452A-AAA0-\n1AF49590F658/2615/Supplemento.pdf Legge sulle fonti del diritto of 7 June 1929,\nlaws and regulations are published in the Italian-language Supplemento per le\nleggi e disposizioni dello Stato della CittÃ  del Vaticano attached to the Acta\nApostolicae Sedis.] It is co-official in Slovenian Istria and in Istria\nCounty in Croatia. The Italian language adopted by the state after the\nunification of Italy is based on Tuscan, which beforehand was a language spoken\nmostly by the upper class of Florentine society. [http://www.italian-language-study.com/italian-language/modern-\nitalian.htm Modern Italian] The Italian Language Retrieved 2010-05-16 Its\ndevelopment was also influenced by other Italian languages and by the Germanic\nlanguages of the post-Roman invaders.\n\nItalian is descended from Latin. Unlike most other Romance languages, Italian\nretains Latin's contrast between short and long consonants. As in most Romance\nlanguages, stress is distinctive. In particular, among the Romance languages,\nItalian is the closest to Latin in terms of vocabulary.\n","linknr":1188,"url":"Italian_language","recorded":1362566891,"links":222,"instances":["linguistics","linguistics","orthography","association","manzoni_novel","digraph","romance","grammar","qualification","grammar"],"pdf":["http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_243_sum_en.pdf","http://www.vaticanstate.va/NR/rdonlyres/FBFEA0E8-B43A-452A-AAA0-1AF49590F658/2615/Supplemento.pdf","http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/infothek/lexikon/bienvenue___login/blank/zugang_lexikon.Document.52217.pdf","http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/infothek/lexikon/bienvenue___login/blank/zugang_lexikon.Document.52217.pdf","http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_243_en.pdf","http://www.chr.up.ac.za/hr_docs/countries/docs/charterfeb04.pdf"],"categories":["Italian language|","Languages of Australia","Languages of Italy","Languages of San Marino","Languages of Slovenia","Languages of Switzerland","Languages of Vatican City","Subject–verb–object languages","Article Feedback 5 Additional Articles"],"headings":["History","Classification","Geographic distribution","Italian dialects and languages","Phonology","Writing system","Sounds","Vocabulary","Grammar","Examples","Sample texts","See also","References and notes","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Flag_of_Europe.svg/22px-Flag_of_Europe.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/03/Flag_of_Italy.svg/22px-Flag_of_Italy.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Flag_of_Switzerland.svg/17px-Flag_of_Switzerland.svg.p